  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is universally classified as a legally prohibited activity. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate (\"clean\") by disguising the true origin of the funds. This activity is illegal because it facilitates criminal enterprises, tax evasion, corruption, and other unlawful activities.\n\nMost countries have established stringent laws and regulations to combat money laundering. These laws typically require financial institutions and other regulated entities to implement robust anti-money laundering (AML) measures, such as customer due diligence, reporting suspicious transactions, and maintaining records. Violations of these laws can result in severe penalties, including fines, imprisonment, and reputational damage. International bodies, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), also play a crucial role in setting global standards to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a criminal offense and is strictly prohibited by law in virtually all jurisdictions worldwide.",
